{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1003: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Are there infinitely many solutions to $\\phi(n)=\\phi(n+1)$, where $\\phi$ is the Euler totient function? Current best: Erd\\H{o}s \\cite{Er85e} says that, presumably, for every $k\\geq 1$ the equation\\[\\phi(n)=\\phi(n+1)=\\cdots=\\phi(n+k)\\]has infinitely many solutions. Erd\\H{o}s, Pomerance, and S\\'{a}rk\\\"{o}zy \\cite{EPS87} proved that the number of $n\\leq x$ with $\\phi(n)=\\phi(n+1)$ is at most\\[\\frac{x}{\\exp((\\log x)^{1/3})}.\\]See [946] for the analogous question with the divisor function. Prize: no. OEIS: A001274. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_6fea18f0d1fafdce","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1003.erdos_1003 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1003.erdos_1003.","id":"vf_c77daa3c68cf4d62","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1003.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_6fea18f0d1fafdce","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:1003","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_c77daa3c68cf4d62","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:1003","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_c77daa3c68cf4d62","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"vf_6fea18f0d1fafdce","trust":"signed"}]